On 12/1/18 1:52 PM, Norman Wilson wrote:
> Bill's half right.  I didn't invent a language; I used what was there.

Can I ask what language you did use?  Was it m4 or something else?

> I decided that the best way to deal with Sendmail's own configuration=20
> language was to treat it as I would the assembly language for a=20
> specialized, irregularly-designed microprocessor:
>=20
> 1.  Understand as well as possible what the instructions actually do;
> 2.  Write the simplest possible program that will get the job done;
> 3.  Avoid extra layers of macros and so on that hide the details, becau=
se=20
> that also hides the irregularities and makes it harder to understand=20
> and debug;
> 4.  By the same reason, don't just copy someone else's program that doe=
s=20
> something complicated; write your own and do things simply.
>=20
> Sendmail has plenty of design flaws (not just in the language), as=20
> I'm sure Eric will acknowledge; but I think the biggest problem people =

> have had with it that most people copied the rather-complicated sample =

> configuration files shipped with the source rather than just reading=20
> the manual, doing a few experiments to understand the behaviour, and=20
> writing something simple.

I see the same lack of understanding in a lot of things.

> On the other hand, I've never quite understood why so many people=20
> treat device drivers as scary and untouchable, copying an existing one =

> and hacking it until it seems to work rather than understanding what=20
> the device actually does and writing a simple program to control it.=20
> So perhaps my brain just doesn't work normally.

For me, I don't know where to get good documentation of what the device=20
actually does and how to make it do it.  I also don't have a good (read: =

any) understanding of the OS / kernels that I'd connect the device to.=20
So, writing software to connect the device (I don't fully comprehend) to =

the OS / kernel (that I don't fully comprehend) in a language (that I'm=20
not fluent in) is an uphill battle for me.  I have great respect and=20
gratitude for the people that do write device drivers.

I don't create the Lego bricks.  But I do try to build interesting and=20
useful things out of the Lego bricks that others have built.



--=20
Grant. . . .
unix || die


